commentBody:
@Super8ing 

I, on the other hand, think this forum is the perfect place for civilly pointing out errors due to imprecisely (or not) reading what was written; errors in fact—with references that can be checked and challenged, if one wishes; errors in logic; and noting the traditional standards, usages, and quirks that have developed over the many decades of the NYT Xword.

Limiting posts to two per day makes no sense to me, as there seems to be no limit to the need for the above.

@Joan 

I was stumped until I said the names out loud, period, quote, etc.

That's a trick I picked up here in the comments a while ago.

@Andrzej 

I have the same problem from time to time. Really ticks me off.

I finally sent tech support and email.

@Greg 
It’s TAXES brosef. You had TAXEd. 

(At least that was my problem. Maybe yours too?)

@Striker 

If it were TAXES, the clue would have to be "puts..."

And no, a video game platform (NES) isn't running the state government of Connecticut.

@SP 
Just found I had that extra volleyball player as well. 

Really solid puzzle!

@Ben

Yes, rock guitarist is what made me finally understand the theme and why the other theme answers made sense. That was a fun moment. And I had the same problem at the bottom because although I’ve heard his name a lot, I always assumed it was spelled Parr. 

One day I’ll memorize the Greek alphabet. But that day is not this day.

@Andrzej I love that you know MARCO from Playstation. I swear, you're more American Teen Boy than I ever was. 

CONEY dog seemed vaguely familiar, like maybe Coney Island. ASIANA and NEYO from crosses, although both sounded vaguely familiar once filled in. And I did get the theme--even found it helpful, although I was very late in coming to it. 

Question now: do I solve Thursday in two minutes, or continue catching up on comments? time will tell. ;)

@latenightsolver 

I think Homer Simpson said it best.  "DOH!"

Wishing you happy puzzling and the joys of discovering the goodies these grids may reveal.  :)

@Andrzej 

Polish sourdough with butter and a little salt sounds heavenly. 

As a big fan of peanut butter, I'm thankful that 1989 saw the arrival of it in Poland. If you can't have peanut butter there is no such thing as democracy (as long as it's not just Skippy brand).

@john ezra 

You're so right! Democracy equals choice, and us Poles had no choice - as to almost anything - before 1989. The peanut butter case illustrates it well.

I don't know the Skippy brand but I think I know what you mean: I only buy 100% peanuts peanut butter, but in the products of some brands 10 or 20% of the contents are additives...

@Pani Korunova 

Respect! I wish I was able to get themes like today's. Apparently I am not smart enough. The only entry that probably would have given the theme away to silly old me was the last one: had I thought a moment about why a slash solves to rock guitarist I would have nailed it. But by the time I got there, the puzzle was almost complete so I did not have to think about it at all. The other themed clues were too opaque for my puny mind.

I saw Guns N' Roses play live in Warsaw in 2022. Axl was not his old self but Slash rocked - it was amazing 🎸

@Sam 

If you want to talk to Barry Ancona, just say so directly 😉.

I knew what the answer would be, but I had a similar problem with it as you do. Let's see what the comments will reveal to us both.

@MB 

NERTS confused me terribly when I first encountered it - in one of the puzzles here, of course: I can't recall ever hearing that in real life or in tv/films/games etc. Then again, I've never lived in America.

Today I was able to recall it in the end, but the word still looks very strange to me.

@Andrzej 
The reason I know NERTS is that Frank Burns, a character in the 1970s TV show MASH used to say it. 
Show was set during the was in Korea in the 1950s.

@John Carson
Mostly I was unhappy with the words that appeared as the hints. 
It could be I was extra cranky because I had one of my worst attempts at connections ever just before playing strands. (No spoilers for connections either, please.)

@Vaer 

Not sure what Briana saw but I see *atria* which perhaps is it.  

Interesting that there is a circumflex artery too.

@Andrzej 

The Connections with two groups of TV show characters was annoying and absurd. 

But I seem to remember one from a few months back that was all movie titles. I loved it, but I’m sure many people hated it.

@Vaer 

I assume that the incomplete Strands games are people who just gave up, either because they got tired of looking or decided they had other things to do. 

At least Connections kicks you out if you make too many mistakes.

@Vaer 

My success rate with Connections is high, and I would have a streak of around 130 if I hadn't stopped playing during the strike. (130 is nothing compared to the streaks some people have for the crossword, but Connections only started tracking streaks last summer.)

I hate not figuring out all four groups and will let the final group simmer for hours if need be. Unless, of course, I get frustrated and just want to know what the connection is.

@Steve L 
There's a little Robyn sparkle there, but not much. 
Every Thursday night I hope for a Friday puzzle from Robyn.  There's only been one this year.

@Michael 

I did it last night, but i remember there being several pop culture answers from around the 1960s.

Whenever I see that, I wonder about the people who were born in the '70s and later.

@Michael 
Yet another baseless accusation that a constructor is using AI.

Rather than defending the work done by real people, posts like this cheapen it by casting doubt over the authenticity of every work of art, whether it be an essay, a painting, or a crossword puzzle.

@chris 

Sounds like a hip hop collaboration.




I'll see myself out.

@Bill

Also from 1914, but there are too many comments to get through for me to research the origin. Chili sauce, mustard, and onions. 😁

Fort Wayne's Famous Coney Island <a href="https://g.co/kgs/R4B3WzC" target="_blank">https://g.co/kgs/R4B3WzC</a>

@Steve L 
Excellent post! I knew CONEY used to mean rabbit, but never knew about the older pronunciation. Hilarious.

There seems to be an opposite phenomenon with Uranus. Few people have the heart to pronounce it YOOR-en-iss. We want the butt jokes.

@Hardroch 

Europe, eh?

Warsaw had 1 300 000 inhabitants in 1939. 700 000 of them died in the war...

@Andrzej 
I am a 66 year old female and did listen to pop music for quite a while in my life including when Guns and Roses first became a thing, but I had no idea that they had a guitarist named Slash until much later.
So why should Nancy

@Andrzej 

There are at least TWO of us....

I don't FEEL weird, but perhaps I'm wrong.

@Nancy 
Your premise is false. Show tunes are NOT popular music, except maybe in NYC. The only one I know is "Mrs Robinson."

I didn't know who Guns N' Roses were when they opened for Motley Crue in 1987, but that changed very quickly.

@Grant 

You haven’t been to see “Wicked,” have you?

I’ve read that early showings have included audience members singing along with the characters.

@Andrzej 

77 here, and have listened to a large variety of music from jazz to classical to showtunes to pop, soft rock, hard rock, dance pop, reggae, and more. I have movements/songs/groups I like and favor, and many more that I have listened to courtesy of radio and streaming. When there are DJs, they often talk about the artists and their music and projects, so it's almost inevitable that one is going to hear names. On some stations, Slash gets mentioned from time to time. He was also seen in the Kens bit on the Oscars.

We've also seen another Guns n Roses member make 38 appearances (AXL Rose) since 1994, although SLASH has only been an answer once (Playable Guitar Hero character).

@JayTee 
I'm Just Ken on the Oscars was just awesome.

I'm going to make the vast generalization that boys and men are much more aware of rock guitarists than women.  To me when listening to rock music, those guitar solos were often something to be endured before getting back to the music.

@Vaer 
Surely not as bad as the drum solos? Keyboard solos?
Rock band solos of any description were pretty tedious, I just endured them all.

@Grant 

I realize that you already hate me and my musical-theater-loving ways, so I'm just going to lean into that and leave this here:

<a href="https://newmusicaltheatre.com/blogs/green-room/broadway-on-the-billboard-charts-1" target="_blank">https://newmusicaltheatre.com/blogs/green-room/broadway-on-the-billboard-charts-1</a>

@Vaer 

Ha! Same here for your vast generalization!

I did remember Slash with a few crossings that made me think of GUITAR and chuckled but it was not automatic, even though I had the other themers all completed.

@Andrew 
Well, that’s more than I knew an hour ago. Like you, I can’t be bothered to Google. I’m never going to play/participate in it. I think our nearest pool is about 15 miles away, so meh.

Thanks for the heads up though.

@Nancy 

What's the motivation for this quiz that is obviously geared toward your specific knowledge base from a specific time period, written when you were offended by people saying a clue referencing a musician from a very popular rock band from 35 years ago is relatively common knowledge.  Is it to try to make the youngs feel inadequate?  To make yourself feel superior in the face of clues beyond your cultural knowledge?  I'm always interested in motivations.

There's almost always trivia that I don't know in a puzzle, and it never bothers me.  Ever.

Nancy,

Enough with the trivia already; 
get with Will and turn it into a crossword.

@Warren 
That's the Hamilton version.  
My autocorrect is totally out of control today.

@Nancy 

I know almost no movie/pop culture trivia, and I did not know who Slash was either. 

As for your pop quiz, the only question I can try to answer is 2) The opening number to My Fair Lady is 'Wouldn't it be Loverly?', I would guess.

@Nancy
My autocorrect and I would be honored if you used our line.  

Also, you may or may not know that Laura Benati does a mean Melania for Stephen Colbert on CBS Late Night.

@HeathieJ 

"[D]on't fret if you don't get it right away, just keep at it with what you can fill out and trust that it will start to make sense."

I've solved over 10,000 crossword puzzles and I still do that all the time.

@Scott 

Yeah, Jack Paar was the killer for me, too.

There's nothing worse than an entry you *know* is right, but isn't.

@Nemma 

I groused the first time my computer Scrabble game played SKEG against me. 

But it stuck in my head.

@Andrzej 

Thank you, good sir! I'm adding Dada Artist to my resume post haste! 

Love it!! :-D

@HeathieJ 

Yeah, I do go by Frank.  In fact, that's my real name--not Francis, not Franklin, just Frank.

I'm not entirely sure why I chose "Francis", other than I didn't want people to assume I'm one of those Frank reprobates that the entertainment industry insists on.😀
